  <div class="trb_ar_hl">
      <span class="trb_ar_hl_k">Opinion </span><h1 class="trb_ar_hl_t" itemprop="headline" >Why Santa Monica is staying in drought mode
        
      </h1>
    </div>
    </header>
 <div class="trb_ar_main">
          <div class="trb_ar_la"><aside class="trb_embed" data-content-id="87856479" data-content-size="leadart" data-content-type="image" data-content-slug="la-1468454417-snap-photo" data-content-subtype="photo" data-role="sc_item imgsize_ratiosizecontainer" data-state="">      <div class="trb_embed_media">         <figure data-role=" delayload  delayload_done imgsize_item" class="trb_embed_imageContainer_figure"><img itemprop="image" data-baseurl="http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo" alt="Drought tolerant plants" class="trb_embed_imageContainer_img" title="Drought tolerant plants" data-c-nd="1999x1124" data-role="imgsize_srcsetdisplayitem" srcset="http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/350/350x197 350w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/400/400x225 400w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/450/450x253 450w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/500/500x281 500w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/550/550x309 550w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/600/600x338 600w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/650/650x366 650w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/700/700x394 700w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/750/750x422 750w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/800/800x450 800w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/850/850x478 850w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/900/900x506 900w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/950/950x534 950w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/1000/1000x563 1000w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/1050/1050x591 1050w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/1100/1100x619 1100w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/1150/1150x647 1150w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/1200/1200x675 1200w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/1400/1400x788 1400w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/1600/1600x900 1600w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/1800/1800x1013 1800w, http://www.trbimg.com/img-5786d519/turbine/la-1468454417-snap-photo/1999/1999x1124 1999w" sizes="(min-width: 1260px) 750px, (min-width: 1060px) calc(100vw - 559px), (min-width: 840px) calc(100vw - 419px), (min-width: 800px) 800px, 100.1vw" /></figure><div class="trb_embed_related"  data-role="lightbox_metadata" >  <span class="trb_embed_related_title">Drought tolerant plants</span>    <div class="trb_embed_related_credit">Los Angeles Times</div>    <div class="trb_embed_related_caption">Water-saving features at a home in Santa Monica include drought-tolerant plants that help hold water in the yard.</div>    <div class="trb_embed_related_credit_and_caption">Water-saving features at a home in Santa Monica include drought-tolerant plants that help hold water in the yard. (Los Angeles Times)</div></div>         </div></aside></div>
          <div
            ><div class="trb_ar_by"
      ><span class="trb_ar_by_nm_pm"
        ><span data-byline-withoutby class="trb_ar_by_nm_au"><span itemprop="author">Dean Kubani</span
></span
          ></span
    ></div
  >
      
      <div class="trb_ar_dateline"><time itemprop="datePublished" class="trb_ar_dateline_time" data-dt="July 14, 2016, 10:00 AM" datetime="2016-07-14T10:00:00PDT"></time>
  </div>
    </div>
            <div itemprop="articleBody">
                    
                        <div class="trb_ar_page"  data-role="pagination_page" data-content-page="1">
                          
      
  
        
      
      <p>Last year, faced with one of the worst droughts in California history, Gov. Jerry Brown issued a mandate to cities across the state to cut water use by 25%.&nbsp;And guess what &#8211; the cuts were successful.&nbsp;Up against a daunting challenge, Californians proved that, when asked, they could come together to meet the task at hand.</p><p>Last month, however, in response to heavy rains filling reservoirs in the northern half of the state last&nbsp;winter, the governor relaxed his conservation mandate.&nbsp;But the drought is not over by any stretch of the imagination &#8212; particularly in the Southland.&nbsp;Only 5 inches of rain fell in the Los Angeles area during the 2015-16 rainy season, significantly below the 14-inch average for the region and the 30 inches of rain that was anticipated due to El Ni&ntilde;o conditions. Hydrologists say we will need at least three years in a row of above-average rainfall to get us back to pre-drought conditions.&nbsp;That scenario seems unlikely, as forecasters are projecting a dry winter this year that would deepen the drought.</p>
  <div class="trb_gptAd trb_ar_main_ad" data-role="adloader adloader_ad delayload delayload_done" data-adloader-size="300x250" data-state="adloader_unloaded"  data-withinviewport-options="bottomOffset=100&topOffset=1000000"  data-adloader-position="articleCube" data-adloader-adtype="articlebottomcube" data-adloader-label ></div
    >
  <aside class="trb_embed" data-content-id="86138805" data-content-size="small" data-content-type="story" data-content-slug="la-ol-el-nino-pollution-water-drought-20160307" data-content-subtype="story" data-role="sc_item  imgsize_ratiosizecontainer " data-state="">        <div class="trb_embed_media">        <span data-content-kicker="Opinion"></span><a class="trb_embed_media_link"  href="/opinion/livable-city/la-ol-el-nino-pollution-water-drought-20160307-story.html" data-content-media-present="true"><figure data-role=" delayload  delayload_done imgsize_item" class="trb_embed_imageContainer_figure"><img itemprop="image" data-baseurl="http://www.trbimg.com/img-56ddd4fb/turbine/la-ol-el-nino-pollution-water-drought-20160307" alt="Our coastal waters are in trouble. Here&apos;s how we can help save them and fight the drought" class="trb_embed_imageContainer_img" title="Our coastal waters are in trouble. Here&apos;s how we can help save them and fight the drought" data-c-nd="2048x1365" /></figure></a><div class="trb_embed_related" data-role="lightbox_metadata" >                      <a class="trb_embed_media_link" href="/opinion/livable-city/la-ol-el-nino-pollution-water-drought-20160307-story.html"><span class="trb_embed_related_title">Our coastal waters are in trouble. Here's how we can help save them and fight the drought</span>        <div class="trb_embed_related_credit">Tom Ford</div>        <div class="trb_embed_related_caption"><p>As a scientist and the executive director of the Bay Foundation, I’ve spent years filling in Angelenos on the important but admittedly unpleasant details of how Los Angeles treats and discharges its sewage and stormwater into the ocean. For decades, this L.A. story had a serious yuck factor. It...</p></div>        <div class="trb_embed_related_credit_and_caption">              <p>As a scientist and the executive director of the Bay Foundation, I’ve spent years filling in Angelenos on the important but admittedly unpleasant details of how Los Angeles treats and discharges its sewage and stormwater into the ocean. For decades, this L.A. story had a serious yuck factor. It...</p> (Tom Ford)</div></a></div>        </div></aside><p>Saving water in a dry climate is hard, and as this drought has progressed we&#8217;ve begun to see signs of what I call &#8220;drought fatigue.&#8221; Although Santa Monica reached its water reduction goal very quickly, our water utility began to see water use start to creep back up in January, and last month it rose by 6%.&nbsp;It is clear that temporary requirements to use less water won&#8217;t solve our problems &#8212; as a society we need to begin thinking differently about this vital resource. It&#8217;s time to finally acknowledge that droughts in the American West aren&#8217;t short-term nuisances &#8212; they are the new normal.&nbsp;There is no way to sustainably go back to our old way of life. In Santa Monica, where we get much of our water from local aquifers, we understand this, which is why we are keeping our drought restrictions in place and are busy planning for a drier future.</p><p>Thankfully, a potential path to water sustainability lies ahead if we choose to take it. New guidelines for the outdoor and indoor use of alternate, non-potable water sources issued by the Los Angeles County Department of Public Health in February make a holistic approach to water management possible. The most promising plan of attack, dubbed &#8220;One Water&#8221; by experts, looks to make use of rainwater, urban runoff, wastewater and even brackish groundwater to create a sustainable and resilient water supply.&nbsp;Instead of the massive, centralized reservoirs-to-pipes-to-drains infrastructure system that we&#8217;ve relied on for centuries, One Water distributes water management technology across the urban landscape.&nbsp;This includes off-the-shelf systems that allow buildings to capture rainwater for use in flush toilets, and small treatment plants that tap into sewer lines under our streets to filter the water that we flush away for reuse.</p><div class="trb_ar_cont" data-ar-cont="Article continues below"></div>
        
      <aside class="trb_ar_sponsoredmod trb_barker_mediaconductor" data-adloader-networktype="mediaconductor" data-role="delayload delayload_item" data-screen-size='desktop' data-withinviewport-options="bottomOffset=100" data-load-method="trb.vendor.mediaconductor.init" data-load-type="method"  data-vendor-mc></aside><p>In our effort to abide by the One Water philosophy, Santa Monica has banned new sprinkler systems.&nbsp;That may sound draconian, but why permit a technology that is 55% efficient at distributing water when there are others that cost about the same, such as drip irrigation, that are 95% efficient?</p><aside class="trb_embed"  data-content-size="small" data-content-type="blurb"
      >
  <div id="trb_em_b_85278850" class="trb_embed_blurb"  data-role="delayload" data-load-type="commentFrame"  style="padding-top:240px;padding-bottom:0%" data-frame-width="100%" data-frame-height="100%"data-frame-class="trb_em_b_if" data-frame-scroll="no">
